  abstract = {Artificial intelligence models perform differently based on the quality and size of the dataset; some require large datasets, while others do well with smaller ones. Although both size and quality are important, maintaining a balance in class distribution is crucial to prevent bias toward one class over another. GANs can produce synthetic medical images to address dataset limitations and class imbalances. However, a central question is whether GAN-generated images keep the key features of the original image classes. This study investigates whether GAN-generated medical images preserve the discriminative features of their original class. We classify the augmented images using a CNN and employ Grad-CAM for visual explanations. The results show that the GAN is largely successful in maintaining the original class features and generates novel and diverse images. Our analysis of the BraTs2020 dataset showed that the CNN classifier reached a 71% accuracy. According to Grad-CAM, relevant anatomical regions were maintained, and SSIM scores (0.67-0.79) indicated that the majority of synthetic images preserved key diagnostic features.},
